reviewText: Here are Clarke Isaac,Jordan Taylor and Zachary Walker Hanson promoting their recent release UNDERNEATH. This concert is a lot like 1998's LIVE FROM ALBERTANE. So Hanson aren't making young girls swoon anymore,big deal! But they still can. The Barry,Robin and Maurice Gibb of Tulsa,Oklahoma will continue to please their fans as long as they live. They will be inducted into the Rock And Roll Hall Of Fame in 2022 or later. This concert audience,like any other Hanson concert,is predominantly female. It rocks,though! If you love Hanson's music,this item is a must for you!
summary: The Hanson Brothers Come Alive Again!

reviewText: With their return to the music scene after a 4 year gap between records, the brothers Hanson have something to prove and I think with this concert and the accompanying album, they proved it. They have returned wiser, more seasoned and better prepared to do what they do best with the passion and natural talent that they have always had. If what you like is real, genuine rock music and folky or sometimes even beatlesque ballads, this is something you may want to check out. This is Hanson at their best, playing live, raw, acoustic music with more passion than any band I have ever had the pleasure of watching perform.
Title: N/A

reviewText: As the proud owner of the oversized, hideous form in the front row of this concert, I can tell you that it came off well both live and on video. While previously released versions (on PPV and in movie theaters) of this concert showcased an abbreviated setlist, this is going to be the most complete version of the concert you can find, with only a miniscule amount of songs (3) missing from the original concert setlist (one of which wasn't even taped in the first place).This disc will also house a trailer for the upcoming documentary that details the struggles they went through as they split with their former label...this is also the reason for the title of this review, as that one will undoubtedly be the most interesting video release the band puts out to date.On a strictly concert-video level, this DVD blows away the two previous concert video releases (Live At The Fillmore & Live From Albertane) in both quality and quantity. This is one of those things that even non-fans may be impressed with in small doses. The low price on this DVD pushes it from 4 stars to 5 stars. An excellent buy.
summary: Currently, this is THE Hanson DVD to buy

reviewText: This DVD recorded in 2003 is a MUST have for any Hanson fan. In this DVD you will watch Issac, Taylor and Zac preforming some of there best known (If only, I will come to you, Penny and Me, MMMBop) songs as well as some songs that were not singles and won't be well known to anyone whos not a Hanson fan (Strong Enough to break, Runway Run,  Deeper, You Never Know...ETC). Add in a few Covers to the mix (Teach your Children and Ain't no sunshine) and you have a winning concert.This is Hanson at there best, showing there true talent. Each brother also gets a solo section to really showcase their talent. The crowd is really into the show, and you feel like you are right there rocking out to them. I'll say it again, a must own for Hanson fans! Not a bad song on this DVD, the only down side is not enoughh features (a interview that was really nice, and the trailer for the Strong Enough to break Documentray). Still a must own. Hanson rocks, and so dose this DVD.

reviewText: If this concert DVD doesn't change minds about Hanson, I don't know what will. The guys are in top form on the last show of their Acoustic '03 tour. My husband and I were at this show, enjoying it chaos-free from the balcony. The songs rocked even harder than I remembered...just try to sit still during "Rip It Up," I dare you!The bonus features of the behind-the-scenes are nice; the whole "oops, we forgot our in-ear monitors" was a wonderful Spinal Tap moment, and the Strong Enough to Break documentary trailer (doc coming in 2005) makes me want to see that thing tomorrow.
